WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.870 --> 00:00:13.820
- So today we're going to talk
about two what I'm calling

00:00:13.820 --> 00:00:16.940
tough nuts, education and healthcare,

00:00:16.940 --> 00:00:20.950
but I want to just begin by
taking stock of where we were

00:00:20.950 --> 00:00:23.660
before we went on the break.

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:27.290
- Right now, the human worker does $50,000

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:29.180
worth of work in a factory.

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:31.190
That income is taxed.

00:00:31.190 --> 00:00:33.333
If the robot comes in
to do the same thing,

00:00:33.333 --> 00:00:38.333
you'd think that we'd tax
the robot at a similar level.

00:00:38.939 --> 00:00:41.772
(energetic music)

00:00:46.123 --> 00:00:49.420
What the world wants is
to take this opportunity

00:00:49.420 --> 00:00:51.775
to make all the goods and
services we have today

00:00:51.775 --> 00:00:53.726
and free up labor.

00:00:53.726 --> 00:00:58.630
Let us do a better job of
reaching out to the elderly,

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:02.700
having smaller class size,
helping kids with special needs.

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:05.647
All of those things where
human empathy and understanding

00:01:05.647 --> 00:01:10.040
are still very, very unique
and we still deal with

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:15.040
an immense shortage of
people to help out there.

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.820
And so, if you can take the
labor that used to do the thing

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:24.430
automation replaces, and both
financially and training-wise

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:27.310
and fulfillment-wise,
have that person go off

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:30.675
and do these other
things, you're net ahead.

00:01:30.675 --> 00:01:35.064
But you can't just give
up that income tax,

00:01:35.064 --> 00:01:37.631
because that's part of
how you've been funding

00:01:37.631 --> 00:01:41.180
that level of human workers.

00:01:41.180 --> 00:01:44.370
Some of it can come on the
profits that are generated

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:47.650
by the labor saving efficiency there.

00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:52.150
Some of it can come directly
in some type of robot tax.

00:01:52.150 --> 00:01:53.810
You know, I don't think
the robot companies

00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:57.893
are going to be outraged
that there might be a tax.

00:01:59.630 --> 00:02:00.793
It's okay.

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:10.540
- So, that was a fairly agreeable
version of a tax proposal,

00:02:12.450 --> 00:02:14.883
which I'll come back to later.

00:02:15.732 --> 00:02:18.070
But this is part five of the course,

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:22.740
focused on what is to be done,
and the bumper sticker that,

00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:26.258
with apologies to Immanuel
Kant, was that politics without,

00:02:26.258 --> 00:02:28.750
policy without politics is empty,

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:32.592
but politics without policy is blind.

00:02:32.592 --> 00:02:36.960
And when we talked about
policy without viable politics,

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:41.960
I gave as examples Piketty's
proposal for global wealth tax

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:46.264
with no identified enforcement mechanisms

00:02:46.264 --> 00:02:51.264
and his more recent proposals
for a European Parliament

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:55.860
that would engage in
redistributive politics

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:58.528
and have trumping power over the existing

00:02:58.528 --> 00:03:01.930
European structures,
even though the attempt

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:05.216
to create such a parliament
had failed because of

00:03:05.216 --> 00:03:09.987
popular hostility to it,
and had instead resulted

00:03:09.987 --> 00:03:13.360
in the Lisbon Treaty.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.055
When we talked about politics
without viable policies,

00:03:18.055 --> 00:03:20.800
politics without viable policies,

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:24.950
I gave us the bumper sticker for that,

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:29.570
the subprime mortgage crisis,
where extremely politically

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:34.570
effective coalitions had been
put together across the aisle

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:39.007
and with lobbyists and industry advocates,

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:45.360
not to mention the advocates
for housing for the poor,

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:50.360
but it produced a train wreck of a policy.

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:55.640
We then focused on the
subject of insecurity,

00:03:55.640 --> 00:04:00.012
arguing that insecurity
is in many respects,

00:04:00.012 --> 00:04:03.210
more important than
inequality and certainly

00:04:03.210 --> 00:04:06.030
than global inequalities for people,

00:04:06.030 --> 00:04:09.851
and made the case that
universal basic income,

00:04:09.851 --> 00:04:13.109
despite the apparent support for it across

00:04:13.109 --> 00:04:17.420
various ideological groups,
that doesn't withstand scrutiny

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:21.820
when you see that the
conservative case for it would

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:27.443
largely result in the abolition
of what we think of as

00:04:27.443 --> 00:04:32.443
the welfare state, Social
Security, Medicare and so on,

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:36.100
so they would easily be
blocking coalitions for that,

00:04:36.100 --> 00:04:40.950
and indeed when you look in
Europe at, where they've held

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:43.610
referendums on this,
such as in Switzerland,

00:04:43.610 --> 00:04:47.743
there's not much support for it.

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:51.827
We talked some about minimum
wage and the difficulties

00:04:51.827 --> 00:04:56.120
of that, particularly
the race to the bottom

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:58.320
or the race out of the country problem

00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:01.556
that accompanies minimum wage politics,

00:05:01.556 --> 00:05:06.556
and instead argued for an
expanded earned income tax credit,

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:10.100
which goes back to the
Nixon administration's

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:13.048
notion of a negative income
tax, and could become

00:05:13.048 --> 00:05:17.530
the basis for a more
effective wage subsidy,

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:21.560
and has been greatly
expanded in recent decades

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:25.590
under Republican and
Democrat administrations.

00:05:25.590 --> 00:05:28.494
And there are also state-based
earned income tax credits,

00:05:28.494 --> 00:05:31.271
which have the advantage
of creating a kind of

00:05:31.271 --> 00:05:35.840
race to the top incentive
in that they become magnets,

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:39.905
states can make themselves
magnets for employment

00:05:39.905 --> 00:05:43.270
because of the employment subsidy.

00:05:43.270 --> 00:05:46.310
Economists will still
complain that this distorts

00:05:46.310 --> 00:05:50.830
labor markets, which it does,
but any policy that attempts

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:54.050
to affect employment at some
level is going to affect

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:56.900
labor markets, and we argue that

00:05:56.900 --> 00:06:00.084
this is a better way to do it.

00:06:00.084 --> 00:06:04.620
We then went on to the idea of universal

00:06:05.630 --> 00:06:08.390
adjustment assistance
and I worked through the

00:06:08.390 --> 00:06:11.160
sort of tragic history of trade investment

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:14.680
and insurance adjustment assistance, where

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:20.770
labor had initially supported
it as a quid pro quo

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:24.520
for the 1962 Trade Act
which reduced tariffs,

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:27.170
but then it was largely not implemented

00:06:27.170 --> 00:06:31.456
by the Johnson administration
that came into office in 1963.

00:06:31.456 --> 00:06:33.670
Nothing was paid out.

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:37.180
In fact, over the next decade
and by the time business

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:42.180
got around to supporting
it, labor had bailed out,

00:06:42.187 --> 00:06:46.390
and it had garnered a
lot of opposition because

00:06:46.390 --> 00:06:51.390
by only supporting people who
lose their jobs from trade,

00:06:51.624 --> 00:06:54.910
this seemed arbitrary from from
the point of view of people

00:06:54.910 --> 00:06:57.210
who lost their jobs for other reasons,

00:06:57.210 --> 00:07:00.410
and indeed when the Reagan
administration effectively

00:07:00.410 --> 00:07:03.110
killed off the program they
made that same argument,

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.207
so it was made both on
the left and the right,

00:07:06.207 --> 00:07:10.394
and we argue, particularly
given the sort of dynamic

00:07:10.394 --> 00:07:13.700
that Bill Gates is referring
to, they have jobs going

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:18.700
in any case increasingly to
technology rather than to trade.

00:07:19.462 --> 00:07:24.462
There should be a Danish style,
much more universal system

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:29.950
of adjustment assistance
that would provide

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:35.240
for relocation, for
retraining across a lifetime.

00:07:35.434 --> 00:07:37.420
And when we think about how might that

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:41.873
sort of adjustment assistance
be funded, as Gates,

00:07:43.010 --> 00:07:46.232
Gates perhaps is a little
naive to think corporations

00:07:46.232 --> 00:07:50.430
will not abolish it, but in
fact this is in the interest

00:07:50.430 --> 00:07:55.040
of business because one thing
that economists will say,

00:07:55.040 --> 00:08:00.040
but it's not obvious to lay
people, is that public education

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:05.090
of any sort is actually
a subsidy to business.

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:08.221
It's a government subsidy
to business by creating

00:08:08.221 --> 00:08:12.660
trained workers that
businesses can then hire,

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:17.300
and so government subsidies
of retraining programs, again,

00:08:17.300 --> 00:08:20.189
is at the end of the day,
a subsidy to business,

00:08:20.189 --> 00:08:24.720
and we make the case in
in my forthcoming book

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.873
with Michael Glass that business leaders

00:08:27.873 --> 00:08:30.250
should be getting behind proposed,

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:32.660
doing what Gates is doing
there, getting behind

00:08:32.660 --> 00:08:37.660
such proposals, because they
will sort of, if you like,

00:08:38.250 --> 00:08:41.470
Tocqueville's self interest
rightly understood,

00:08:41.470 --> 00:08:45.893
it really is in businesses'
interest to support the creation

00:08:45.893 --> 00:08:50.893
of a perpetually re-educatable
workforce that's going to be

00:08:51.655 --> 00:08:54.990
flexible in ways that
are going to be required

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:58.850
by the demands of the 21st century.

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:03.208
So, today's agenda is to talk
about two other challenges:

00:09:03.208 --> 00:09:07.517
K through 12 education and
universal health insurance,

00:09:07.517 --> 00:09:11.924
and they're very vexed
subjects in America,

00:09:11.924 --> 00:09:15.220
and they're vexed subjects partly because

00:09:15.220 --> 00:09:18.039
there are two other
features of the American

00:09:18.039 --> 00:09:23.039
political order, which make
it very extremely difficult

00:09:23.645 --> 00:09:28.645
to enact a lot of social
policies and these are worse here

00:09:28.910 --> 00:09:32.320
or more challenging here
than in many other countries.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:34.430
The first is fiscal federalism.

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:36.510
We've referred to this
earlier in the course,

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:38.950
you might recall, when I talked about the

00:09:38.950 --> 00:09:42.530
deinstitutionalization
of psychiatric patients

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:45.218
in connection with
rising prison populations

00:09:45.218 --> 00:09:50.176
and with the discovery of antidepressants

00:09:50.176 --> 00:09:55.176
and anti-psychotropic drugs
to repress things like

00:09:56.450 --> 00:10:00.991
schizophrenia, when in the 1960s and 70s,

00:10:00.991 --> 00:10:04.324
this led to many people who had previously

00:10:04.324 --> 00:10:09.324
lived their whole lives
in psychiatric hospitals

00:10:09.712 --> 00:10:13.600
to be released, but it
was also a time of great

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:15.860
fiscal crisis in many of the states,

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:18.727
and so those savings were
put to the bottom line

00:10:18.727 --> 00:10:22.150
of state budgets and instead
those people wound up

00:10:22.150 --> 00:10:25.193
in American cities where there was not,

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:29.809
there were no resources
for them, and consequently,

00:10:29.809 --> 00:10:32.910
many of them then wound up
back in the prison system.

00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:36.334
And so this is the kind
of the dark side of

00:10:36.334 --> 00:10:41.070
fiscal federalism that we
have a very decentralized

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:44.202
federal system, unlike say
the German federal system,

00:10:44.202 --> 00:10:46.960
where there are very clear demarcations,

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:50.610
because the whole federal
system was designed at once,

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:53.210
of what's the risk, so
there are clear demarcations

00:10:53.210 --> 00:10:57.530
of what is the responsibility
of which level of government,

00:10:57.530 --> 00:11:00.020
whereas we have a kind
of bottom up federalism

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:05.020
that was created
piecemeal, and power is not

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:07.630
explicitly delegated to
the federal government,

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:11.020
reside with the states,
some things are the province

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:14.610
of cities and not the
responsibilities of states,

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:18.750
and so it's very easy for things
to fall through the cracks

00:11:18.750 --> 00:11:22.270
and we will see as we talk
about education and healthcare

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:26.620
that this decentralized
character of American federalism

00:11:26.620 --> 00:11:31.620
makes it extremely
difficult to enact policies

00:11:31.783 --> 00:11:33.836
that in other countries would be done

00:11:33.836 --> 00:11:36.500
as a matter of national policy

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:39.730
or what we would call federal policy here.

00:11:39.730 --> 00:11:43.218
The other is that the
that the American system

00:11:43.218 --> 00:11:48.218
is much more subject to
what some social scientists

00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:53.297
refer to as path dependence,
and the idea of path dependence

00:11:53.297 --> 00:11:57.690
is if, as the name implies,
as you start heading down

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:00.746
one path, and maybe you take a left fork,

00:12:00.746 --> 00:12:03.987
then you're confronted
with some other forks,

00:12:03.987 --> 00:12:07.300
but you no longer have the
option of the right fork

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:11.500
you would have taken, perhaps
if you'd seen, later on,

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:14.810
what were the consequences
of going on the left fork.

00:12:14.810 --> 00:12:17.080
And so this is the idea
of path dependence,

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:20.057
things that are done
earlier shaped the choices

00:12:20.057 --> 00:12:22.602
of things that are coming later.

00:12:22.602 --> 00:12:26.633
Now if you have a very
centralized political system,

00:12:26.633 --> 00:12:30.340
that may not matter very
much, so say in Britain

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:33.230
where they have strong parties,
I'll talk more about that

00:12:33.230 --> 00:12:37.140
on Thursday, they can do
things like nationalized

00:12:37.140 --> 00:12:40.822
and denationalized and
renationalized British rail.

00:12:40.822 --> 00:12:45.100
It's relatively simple
because most political power

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:49.840
resides in the House of Commons,
so they can make decisions

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:52.780
that are decisive, and they can revert.

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:55.615
If the incentives change
or new information arises,

00:12:55.615 --> 00:12:58.157
they can make a different policy.

00:12:58.157 --> 00:13:02.343
Our system is designed to be
extremely difficult to change,

00:13:02.343 --> 00:13:07.343
and so there are multiple
veto players in the system,

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:12.063
as we've discussed in earlier
classes with the bicameralism,

00:13:12.063 --> 00:13:15.640
with the separation of powers,
with the presidentialism,

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:19.575
with the federalism, with
the Senate filibuster rules

00:13:19.575 --> 00:13:24.575
and with the over
representation of small states

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:27.820
in the Senate, with the court.

00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:32.820
All of these veto players
mean that the choices made,

00:13:33.352 --> 00:13:37.874
once they're embedded, are
very difficult to change,

00:13:37.874 --> 00:13:40.730
and we talked about
this in connection also

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:44.050
with embedding proximate
goals, that you want to make

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:46.690
your approximate goals
difficult to change.

00:13:46.690 --> 00:13:51.690
And so FDR, in the case of
Social Security, found a way

00:13:51.712 --> 00:13:56.712
to use the inertia in the system
to protect Social Security.

00:13:57.630 --> 00:14:01.700
But the inertia is there, and
it means that path dependence

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.503
is a much bigger deal in the US system

00:14:04.503 --> 00:14:06.491
than in other systems.

00:14:06.491 --> 00:14:11.491
And so as we go through these
two examples of K through 12

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:14.733
education and healthcare,
you're going to see

00:14:14.733 --> 00:14:18.430
the fiscal federalism and
the inertia that privileges

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:21.770
path dependent popping up
again and again and again

00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:25.449
and making, creating
substantially bigger challenges

00:14:25.449 --> 00:14:30.410
for these sorts of policies in
the US than we see elsewhere.

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:34.920
So I asked you to read the
Dale Russakoff's "The Prize"

00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:39.920
about New Jersey educational
reform and let's just

00:14:40.680 --> 00:14:45.680
get our minds around that
with a look at this video.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.840
- Republican Governor Chris Christie,

00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:51.570
Democratic Mayor of Newark, Cory Booker

00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:54.510
and the founder of
Facebook, Mark Zuckerberg,

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:58.490
are putting politics
aside to help turn around

00:14:58.490 --> 00:15:00.780
the failing public schools
in Newark, New Jersey.

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:04.220
This is the first time all three
of you really come together

00:15:04.220 --> 00:15:07.204
to talk about this big idea.

00:15:07.204 --> 00:15:09.800
So, Mayor Booker, for
those who don't know,

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:11.340
what's the big news?

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:13.290
- Well, we've been talking
for quite some time

00:15:13.290 --> 00:15:15.920
about creating a bold new paradigm

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:17.980
for educational excellence in
the country to show the way,

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:19.970
to put the people of the city of Newark

00:15:19.970 --> 00:15:21.667
really in the driver's
seat and the focal point,

00:15:21.667 --> 00:15:24.490
and to work to get all the
assets and resources we need

00:15:24.490 --> 00:15:26.226
to give to them to succeed.

00:15:26.226 --> 00:15:28.920
- So, Governor Christie,
what are you committing to?

00:15:28.920 --> 00:15:30.160
What are you committing to?

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:32.300
- What I'm committed to
is changing the schools

00:15:32.300 --> 00:15:33.524
in the city where I was born,

00:15:33.524 --> 00:15:36.217
I spent the first years of
my life, and Mayor Booker

00:15:36.217 --> 00:15:40.230
is going to be the point
person, our lead guy in Newark

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.820
in helping to develop
this entirely new plan

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:45.470
of how to reform the
education system in Newark

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:47.039
and create a national model.

00:15:47.039 --> 00:15:48.580
I'm empowering him to do that.

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:49.843
I'm in charge of the public schools

00:15:49.843 --> 00:15:51.880
in the city of Newark as Governor.

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:54.127
I'm going to empower Mayor
Booker to develop that plan

00:15:54.127 --> 00:15:56.920
and to implement it with a
superintendent of schools

00:15:56.920 --> 00:15:58.700
that we're going to pick together.

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:00.210
- I think that is so fantastic.

00:16:00.210 --> 00:16:03.120
(audience applauds)

00:16:03.120 --> 00:16:06.393
I think that is so fantastic.

00:16:06.393 --> 00:16:09.040
In this age of red states and blue states

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:12.098
and everybody being so
partisan about everything,

00:16:12.098 --> 00:16:14.350
the fact that you all would come together,

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:15.643
did that ever enter
into it, the politics of

00:16:15.643 --> 00:16:18.090
you're a Republican and he's a Democrat?

00:16:18.090 --> 00:16:19.553
- No, it's about the children.

00:16:19.553 --> 00:16:21.324
I mean, you go to Newark.

00:16:21.324 --> 00:16:24.324
(audience applauds)

00:16:25.601 --> 00:16:28.920
Go to Newark and you watch,
